    "I bought a house built in 1997. The home inspector said everything was 'functional.' That word — functional — did a lot of heavy lifting. Within two years, the water heater gave out, the dishwasher stopped draining, and the garage door opener died. All 'functional' at the time of inspection. All dead within 24 months. The inspector wasn't wrong — they were functional. But functional and 'not about to fail' are very different things. A home warranty would've covered all three breakdowns for less than the cost of the water heater alone.",
    "Last Thanksgiving, I was hosting 14 people. The oven preheated to 350 and then... nothing. It stopped heating. At 10 AM. With a 20-pound turkey sitting on the counter. I spent the next 30 minutes in a panic spiral — calling repair companies (closed for the holiday), texting neighbors (nobody answered), considering deep-frying the turkey in my driveway. We ended up ordering catering for $400. A home warranty with 24/7 holiday service would've dispatched a tech that morning. Instead, I served overpriced restaurant turkey to my family and swore I'd never be caught without coverage again.",
    "I rent out my first home. The tenants called at 11 PM on a Wednesday — the toilet was overflowing and they couldn't stop it. I'm 45 minutes away. I called every plumber in their area. Nobody available until morning. The water ran for six more hours before someone got there. Damage to the bathroom floor: $1,900. Plumber bill: $350. Total: $2,250 because I couldn't get a professional there fast enough. A home warranty's 24/7 dispatch network exists specifically for moments like this. That $2,250 lesson bought me a warranty the next morning.",
    "I was FaceTiming my parents when I noticed the ceiling behind my mom had a brown water stain. 'Oh, that?' she said. 'It's been there a few weeks.' A few weeks. An active leak above her living room ceiling had been spreading for weeks because she didn't want to 'bother anyone' or spend money on a plumber. That stain represented a burst pipe, ceiling damage, and potential mold — easily $3,000-5,000 in repairs. With a home warranty, she could've called at no risk and no stress. One service fee. Instead, the delay turned a $300 pipe fix into a potential insurance claim.",
